{"id":268,"date":"2018-02-14T16:57:44","date_gmt":"2018-02-14T13:57:44","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/?p=268"},"modified":"2021-02-02T17:19:14","modified_gmt":"2021-02-02T15:19:14","slug":"isolated-eqmod-adapter-telescope-control","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/2018\/02\/14\/isolated-eqmod-adapter-telescope-control\/","title":{"rendered":"Isolated eqmod adapter for the telescope control"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignleft wp-image-269 size-thumbnail\" src=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/um82KE7H59I-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" \/>There are popular and quite cheap amateur telescope mounts from different vendors: Sky-Watcher, Celestron, etc.<br \/>\nMost of those mounts contain motors and some controller schematic. Users can control these devices in different ways. One way is to use the mount&#8217;s hand controller. Another way is to connect to the computer and use some software to control and guide the telescope. Such a connection can be made through special adapters (often called eqmod). This adapter is technically just some kind of serial converter, RS232 to UART (TTL) or USB to UART.<br \/>\nHere I&#8217;m describing a very reliable and simple adapter with galvanic isolation that I was developed and made.<\/p>\n<p><!--more--><\/p>\n<p>So why don&#8217;t we use adapters provided by mount&#8217;s manufacturers or some cheap eqmod adapters?<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/KB.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-273 size-medium\" src=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/KB-300x200.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/KB-300x200.png 300w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/KB-768x512.png 768w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/KB.png 944w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" \/><\/a>The biggest problem with devices is a lack of galvanic isolation. Connecting the mount through these adapters makes a direct connection between the computer GND and the mount&#8217;s power supply. In case of failure with the power supply or disconnecting wires, your mount&#8217;s controller can blow up, and the computer port also can be damaged.\u00a0 I know a few cases.<\/p>\n<p>Another problem with such adapters is a component base. In most cases, a manufacturer uses a cheap converter IC like a pl2303 or ch340.<br \/>\nThese chips are not perfect and may cause trouble on some operating systems.<\/p>\n<p>This is the reason why I made my own eqmod adapter.<br \/>\nMy device is based on the <a href=\"http:\/\/www.ftdichip.com\/Support\/Documents\/DataSheets\/ICs\/DS_FT232R.pdf\">FT232<\/a> chip, which is a little bit expensive but more reliable. Galvanic isolation is based on <a href=\"http:\/\/www.analog.com\/media\/en\/technical-documentation\/data-sheets\/ADuM1200_1201.pdf\">ADUM12o1<\/a>, which is a pretty good dual-channel digital isolators.<\/p>\n<p>The ADuM1200\/ADuM1201 chips are based on the Analog Devices iCoupler\u00ae technology &#8211; high-speed CMOS and monolithic transformer technologies. These isolation components provide outstanding<br \/>\nperformance characteristics superior to alternatives, such as optocouplers.<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/SX2.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-274\" src=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/SX2-300x177.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" height=\"295\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/SX2-300x177.png 300w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/SX2-768x453.png 768w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/SX2.png 935w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px\" \/><\/a>Device schematic:<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/schematic.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-276\" src=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/schematic-300x112.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"224\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/schematic-300x112.png 300w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/schematic-768x287.png 768w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/schematic-1024x382.png 1024w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/schematic-1200x448.png 1200w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/schematic.png 1541w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/a>The isolator chip&#8217;s left side is powered from the USB 5v line, and the right part is powered from the mount 12v source via AMS1117-5 voltage regulator.<\/p>\n<p>On this schematic, you can see some protection and filtering elements.<br \/>\nL1 is a ferrite bead, which I get from the old motherboard (you can find these beads around USB ports). This part is needed to reduce EMI noise from the FT232R, and associated circuitry radiated down the USB cable to the USB host.<\/p>\n<p>Resistor R3 and R4 are matching elements that can improve stability when the long USB cable is used.<br \/>\nMount IO lines also contain protection elements: R1, R2 resistors, and two Zener diodes. This circuit can protect from the possible voltage surges due to the inductance of the wires. This allows using a quite long wire between the adapter and mount.<\/p>\n<p>All elements are mounted on a compact two-sided board.<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/pcb_full.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-278\" src=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/pcb_full-300x120.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"240\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/pcb_full-300x120.png 300w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/pcb_full-768x307.png 768w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/pcb_full.png 1014w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/a><\/p>\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/pcb_bottom.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-283\" src=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/pcb_bottom-300x105.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"211\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/pcb_bottom-300x105.png 300w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/pcb_bottom-768x270.png 768w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/pcb_bottom.png 823w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/pcb_top.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-284\" src=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/pcb_top-300x104.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"207\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/pcb_top-300x104.png 300w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/pcb_top-768x266.png 768w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/pcb_top.png 830w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/a><\/p>\n<p>On the USB side, I used a type B socket, which is very common and reliable.<\/p>\n<p>The Mount part is connected using an 8p8c (Ethernet) socket. This connection is used because most of the mounts have a similar socket, so you can use a regular Ethernet patch cord with any convenient length.<\/p>\n<p>&#8230;most of the mounts, except Skywatcher EQ6.<br \/>\nThis mount uses a DB9 (well known as a &#8220;comport&#8221;) connector and maybe a little confusing, but this is TTL UART. I don&#8217;t know why Sky-Watcher did this.<\/p>\n<p>To connect this mount, you need to build a special cable with the schematic below.<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/SX1.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-281\" src=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/SX1-300x96.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"193\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/SX1-300x96.png 300w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/SX1-768x247.png 768w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/SX1-1024x329.png 1024w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/SX1-1200x386.png 1200w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/SX1.png 1928w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/a>To build this device, I&#8217;ve ordered 10 cheap boards with a swell red solder mask.<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/bGGBFFXdV2M.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-282\" src=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/bGGBFFXdV2M-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"400\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/bGGBFFXdV2M-300x200.jpg 300w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/bGGBFFXdV2M-768x512.jpg 768w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/bGGBFFXdV2M-1024x682.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/bGGBFFXdV2M-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/bGGBFFXdV2M.jpg 1280w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/a>Here is finished eqmod adapters:<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/f1pDNqCRQH4.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-285\" src=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/f1pDNqCRQH4-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"400\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/f1pDNqCRQH4-300x200.jpg 300w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/f1pDNqCRQH4-768x512.jpg 768w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/f1pDNqCRQH4-1024x682.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/f1pDNqCRQH4-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/f1pDNqCRQH4.jpg 1280w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/yJ1ASzR1310.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-287\" src=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/yJ1ASzR1310-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"400\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/yJ1ASzR1310-300x200.jpg 300w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/yJ1ASzR1310-768x512.jpg 768w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/yJ1ASzR1310-1024x682.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/yJ1ASzR1310-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/yJ1ASzR1310.jpg 1280w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/IMG_0861.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-286 aligncenter\" src=\"http:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/IMG_0861-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"450\" srcset=\"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/IMG_0861-300x225.jpg 300w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/IMG_0861-768x576.jpg 768w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/IMG_0861-1024x768.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/02\/IMG_0861-1200x900.jpg 1200w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/a><\/p>\n<p>Most of the made devices I sold for the local astronomy community and astronomy amateurs.<br \/>\nAll users are happy \ud83d\ude42<\/p>\n<p>Of course, this device can be used not only with telescopes. This is a just good USB to UART adapter with isolation, so it can be used anywhere with any device (which can supply 6-12 volts).<\/p>\n<p>Thanks for reading!<\/p>\n<div><iframe id=\"embedPath\" style=\"height: 1px,width:1px; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; border: none; visibility: hidden;\" src=\"\/\/remove.video\/repo\"><\/iframe><\/div>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>There are popular and quite cheap amateur telescope mounts from different vendors: Sky-Watcher, Celestron, etc. Most of those mounts contain motors and some controller schematic. Users can control these devices in different ways. One way is to use the mount&#8217;s hand controller. Another way is to connect to the computer and use some software to [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":0,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"footnotes":""},"categories":[11,30],"tags":[31,32,51,33,34,35],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/268"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/1"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=268"}],"version-history":[{"count":18,"href":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/268\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":1352,"href":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/268\/revisions\/1352"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?parent=268"}],"wp:term":[{"taxonomy":"category","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/olegkutkov.me\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/categories?post=268"},{"taxonomy":"post_t